 early modern era to analyze how material objects express, shape, complicate, and extend human concepts of time and how people commemorate time differently. It examines conceptual aspects of time, such as the categories women and men use to define it, and the somatic, lived experiences of time ranging between an instant and the course of family life. Drawing on a wide array of textual and material primary sources, this book assesses the ways that gender and other categories of difference affect understandings of time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTimexSex differencesxHistoryy16th century. 0aTimexSex differencesxHistoryy17th century. 0aTimexSocial aspectsxHistoryy16th century. 0aTimexSocial aspectsxHistoryy17th century. 0aTimexSociological aspectsxHistoryy16th century. 0aTimexSociological aspectsxHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aGender, history of time, temporality, early modern cultural studies.1 aAnderson, Penelope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbaccia, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Elizabeth S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoolidge, Grace E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCope, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrachiolo, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolan, Frances E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDowd, Michelle M., eco